
// Playwright Advanced POM Patterns — Quiz (20 questions, GIFT, English)

::Q1: What problem does a Deep BasePage primarily solve in large test suites?::
{
=Reducing repeated logic by centralizing navigation hooks, waiting logic, and shared helpers
~Improving screenshot resolution
~Replacing the need for Page Objects entirely
~Speeding up browser launch times
}

::Q2: What is the purpose of the onNavigated() hook in BasePage?::
{
=To allow subclasses to add page‑specific readiness checks after navigation
~To disable auto-waiting temporarily
~To automatically generate locators
~To override Playwright’s routing system
}

::Q3: In a Fluent API, why should methods return Promise<this>?::
{
=To ensure chaining works correctly across inheritance hierarchies
~To force all methods to return void
~To prevent subclasses from defining their own methods
~To disable async execution
}

::Q4: Which of the following is a benefit of Fluent API chaining?::
{
=Improves readability by making test steps read like a narrative
~Reduces the number of locators on a page
~Disables network requests automatically
~Eliminates the need for BasePage
}

::Q5: What is the main issue with eager locator initialization?::
{
=All locators are created immediately even if not needed, increasing noise and fragility
~Locators become immutable
~Playwright refuses to evaluate them
~They cannot be used inside tests
}

::Q6: What characterizes a lazy locator implemented with a getter?::
{
=It is created only when accessed
~It is cached automatically
~It cannot accept parameters
~It must be declared in the constructor
}

::Q7: When should memoized lazy locators be used?::
{
=When the locator is deeply chained and used many times
~When the locator must always be recreated
~When the locator uses global CSS only
~When the page has no dynamic elements
}

::Q8: Which scenario requires a dynamic locator method rather than a property?::
{
=Selecting an item based on a runtime value (e.g., getRowByName(name))
~Selecting the page title
~Finding a static header element
~Accessing a permanent sidebar
}

::Q9: What is the purpose of AuthenticatedPage in an inheritance hierarchy?::
{
=To provide shared navigation components and readiness checks for logged-in pages
~To disable user login tests
~To manage service workers
~To handle screenshot generation
}

::Q10: Which method in BaseFormPage determines whether form submission succeeded?::
{
=submitForm()
~onNavigated()
~fill()
~validateInputs()
}

::Q11: What is the primary use case for mixins in Playwright POM architecture?::
{
=Adding cross-cutting behaviors (search, bulk actions) without deep inheritance chains
~Replacing all Page Objects
~Managing browser contexts
~Creating test-specific fixtures
}

::Q12: What requirement must a class satisfy to be used with a mixin?::
{
=It must have a page property
~It must implement BasePage directly
~It must include a flow object
~It must not use lazy locators
}

::Q13: What is the primary purpose of the Page Factory pattern?::
{
=To centralize Page Object construction and reduce direct use of "new"
~To create browser contexts automatically
~To generate TypeScript interfaces
~To replace Playwright fixtures
}

::Q14: How does a multi-step Flow Object differ from a Page Object?::
{
=It orchestrates multiple pages into a single reusable journey
~It replaces all page components
~It manages low-level selectors directly
~It is only used for login tests
}

::Q15: Why should a method that transitions to another page return Promise<NextPage>?::
{
=To allow chaining into the next page's API immediately
~To avoid using async/await
~To remove the need for a Page Factory
~To disable network idle waits
}

::Q16: What is a key advantage of using Flow Objects for complex workflows?::
{
=They encapsulate multi-page steps, reducing duplication across tests
~They eliminate the need for API mocking
~They ensure tests never fail
~They auto-generate screenshots
}

::Q17: Which pattern helps combine multiple behaviors (e.g., search + bulk actions) into a single page?::
{
=Mixins
~Lazy locators
~Flow Objects
~Factories
}

::Q18: In advanced Page Object design, what are eager locators best suited for?::
{
=Elements that always exist on initial page load
~Conditional UI blocks
~Expensive nested locators
~Items requiring parameters
}

::Q19: What should a test using PageFactory typically avoid?::
{
=Instantiating Page Objects manually with "new"
~Using fixtures
~Calling Playwright APIs
~Using async/await syntax
}

::Q20: What is the overarching benefit of using all advanced POM patterns together?::
{
=Highly maintainable, scalable, and readable automation architecture
~Fewer browser restarts
~Automatic network throttling
~Built-in visual comparison features
}

